-      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Week 5 of the AI governance pilot is Iterate & Inherit and asks participants to give the build to a teammate, watch where it breaks, and produce a v2 | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 section, header: \"Week 4 was build. Week 5 is iterate. Take what you built, give it to a teammate, watch where it breaks, fix it.\")\nClaim: Week 5 Challenge instruction \"cut what's thin, sharpen what's vague, name the human checkpoint that has to stay\" | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 Challenge box: \"Take the teammate's feedback from Week 4. Cut what's thin, sharpen what's vague, name the human checkpoint that has to stay.\")\nClaim: The capstone door opens Week 5 with the Week 4 build as the seed | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 lead paragraph: \"The capstone door opens this week — your Week 4 build is the seed.\")\nClaim: AI Friday is the pilot's weekly group session where participants bring iteration work | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html — recurring AI Friday cadence starting Week 2)\nEditorial: The two-prompt Diff-Then-Decide loop (KEEP / FIX / CUT changelist, then constrained rewrite that touches only FIX items) is Preston's tactical move for Week 5 iteration. It mirrors the iterative-refinement pattern Anthropic recommends across prompt engineering documentation but the specific two-prompt structure and column labels are Preston's pedagogical framing.\nEditorial: Framing \"regeneration\" as the trap of one-shot iteration (a fresh prompt with no record of what changed) is Preston's diagnostic.\nEditorial: \"The capstone seed lives in the FIX column you signed off on. The v2 chat is downstream of that decision.\" is Preston's pedagogical close, tying the tactical loop back to the Week 5 capstone-scoping move.\nEditorial: Resource URL points to the pilot hub root; Week 5 block is currently display:none in pilot_hub.html as of 2026-05-05 morning. Pilot administrator will unhide the block on the cadence schedule. The Week 5 Challenge text cited above is in the source HTML and will surface when the block reveals.\nAdversarial review 20260505: Em-dash count: 0 (well under the 2-per-piece limit). Banned phrases scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate (metaphorical), landscape (metaphorical), ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align, transformative, empower, myriad, multifaceted, pivotal, spearhead, showcase, underscore, doing the heavy lifting, the real question is, what most people miss, this is where it gets interesting, it's not about, deep dive, unpack, move the needle, at the end of the day, however, moreover, furthermore, additionally, serves as, stands as, represents, functions as, operates as, groundbreaking, game-changing, revolutionary, passionate about, excited to share, the real story, here's the thing. Contrastive constructions (\"X, not Y\" / \"not X but Y\" / \"isn't X — it's Y\"): zero. Rhetorical questions in body: zero. Opens with concrete fact (Week 5 challenge asks for a v2). Closes with declarative landing (\"The v2 chat is downstream of that decision.\"). Word count main body: 261 (inside 240–280 band). Try This: 52 (inside 40–80 band). Each Editorial framing is tagged. Each external claim traces to pilot_hub.html or the AI Fluency framework, no invented statistics. Tip register: addresses participants directly via \"your\" and \"you\" without descending into TED-talk language.",
+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Week 4 of the AI governance pilot is Build Worth Keeping; the challenge requires loading at least one outside source and writing it into the procedure | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 4 \"This Week's Challenge — Build Worth Keeping\" box, step 2: \"Build the v1. Project or Skill. Load at least one outside source — a research doc, a peer-org playbook, a verified data table, the brand guide, an Anthropic skill — and write it into the procedure.\")\nClaim: Outside-source examples (research doc, peer playbook, verified data table, brand guide, Anthropic skill) | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 4 challenge step 2 — verbatim list)\nClaim: Three customization vectors are org context, outside authority, and workflow shape | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 4 \"The Customization Play\" block names exactly these three vectors)\nClaim: Customization is encoded in the custom-instructions block (Projects) or SKILL.md (Skills) | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 4 customization vectors block: \"Encoded in custom instructions or SKILL.md\")\nClaim: Verbatim phrase \"earns its keep\" framing the Week 4 build standard | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 4 lead paragraph: \"This week you decide what passes the bar — then you build one team-level asset that earns its keep.\")\nClaim: Five-question Build Filter (Frequency, Variability, Inheritance, Stakes, Substitution) — referenced indirectly via \"the build that earns its keep\" frame | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 4 \"Leadership Lens — The Build Filter\" block; the briefing does not enumerate the filter, it depends on the existing pilot framing for which builds qualify)\nEditorial: The three-step Extract / Filter / Encode tactical procedure is Preston's operational decomposition of Week 4's outside-source-loading guidance. The pilot tells participants to load a source; this briefing gives them the move that turns loading into encoding.\nEditorial: Framing the failure mode as \"pasting the source into a reference file and assuming Claude will read it\" is Preston's diagnostic — derived from observed patterns in early-stage Project use, not a quoted source.\nEditorial: Verbatim extraction prompt (\"Read this document. Extract every concrete instruction, threshold, or anti-pattern...\") is Preston's tactical prompt template, designed to surface decision-relevant rules rather than narrative summary.\nEditorial: Closing tie-back to \"a build that earns its keep\" loops the tip explicitly to the Week 4 frame so participants recognize this as a Week 4 move.\nAdversarial review 20260505 (rev 2 — corrected from a Week 5 framing in rev 1 to the actual visible Week 4 in pilot_hub.html). Em-dash count: 0. Banned phrases scanned and absent: leverage, utilize, delve, navigate (metaphorical), landscape (metaphorical), ecosystem, synergy, robust, holistic, stakeholders, foster, enhance, align, transformative, empower, myriad, multifaceted, pivotal, spearhead, showcase, underscore, doing the heavy lifting, the real question is, what most people miss, this is where it gets interesting, deep dive, unpack, move the needle, at the end of the day, however, moreover, furthermore, additionally, serves as, stands as, represents, functions as, operates as, groundbreaking, game-changing, revolutionary, passionate about, excited to share, the real story, here's the thing. Contrastive constructions (\"X, not Y\" / \"not X but Y\" / \"isn't X — it's Y\"): zero. Earlier draft contained \"extraction, not attachment\"; rewritten in pre-commit pass to declarative \"Extraction is the move.\" Rhetorical questions in body: zero. Opens with concrete fact (Week 4 challenge requirement). Closes with declarative landing tying the tip to the Week 4 frame. Word count main body: 266 (inside 240–280 band). Try This: 55 (inside 40–80 band). Tip register: directly addresses participants via \"you\" / \"your\" with verbatim prompt template they can paste.",
